Chapter 19:
- Q: What happen if the translation address in TLB (Translation Lookaside
     Buffer) is out of date?
- Q: What is the policy to decide which memory translation stay or removed in
     TLB?
  A: One common approach is Least Recently Used (LRU) policy, which remove
     TLB entry that are not used recently.
     Another approach is to randomly remove TLB entry (the Random policy).
- Q: What is spatial locality?
  A: Spatial locality is the assumption that if a program accessed memory at
     address `n`, the program will likely access memory near address `n` later
     on. Think of accessing an array, after accessing one element, we might
     access the next element too.
- Q: What is temporal locality?
  A: Temporal locality is the assumption that an instruction or data item that
     has been recently accessed will likely be re-accessed later on. Think of
     loop variables or instructions in a loop, they are accessed repeatedly
     over time.
- Q: What is the lifetime of TLB entries (until the TLB entry become invalid)?
- Q: What is fully associative in TLB means
     (from "TLB Contents: What's In There?" section)?
- A: Fully associative in TLB means that any given translation can be anywhere
     in the TLB, and the hardware will search the entire TLB in parallel to
     find the desired translation.
- Q: How to manage TLB contents when switching between processes?
  A: Some hardware systems provide an Address Space Identifier (ASID) in
     the TLB, so we can use ASID as the identifier to get the translation from
     TLB for specific process.

Chapter 20:
- Q: If linear page table need 1 register to locate the page table (assuming we
     have TLB miss), how many registers we need to locate the page table in
     2-level or 3-level page table?
- A: We only need 1 register regardless of the level of page table. We store the
     highest level of page table reference in the register and fetch the highest
     level page table entry from RAM to get the next level page table reference.
     We keep fetching the page table entry until we got the physical address and
     fetch the data from those physical address.
     References:
     - https://stackoverflow.com/a/66626310
     - https://stackoverflow.com/a/66453599
- Q: Do we keep changing the content of register when going through the
     multi-level page table entry?
- Q: How many memory references are needed to perform each lookup in a 2-level
     page table from simulation?
- A: There are 3 memory references needed to perform in each lookup. 1 memory
     reference for the PDE (highest PTE) address, 1 memory reference for the
     PTE (middle PTE) address, and 1 memory reference for the data in physical
     memory address (?).
- Q: How do you think the memory reference to the page table will behave in the
     cache? Will they lead to lots of cache hits or misses?
- A: It depends on the memory that we need to access. If we constantly access
     the memory from the same page entry (either PDE or PTE), we might have more
     cache hits (because of spatial locality). But if we need to constantly
     access the memory from different page entry, we might have more cache
     misses (?).

Chapter 21:
- Q: Do we immediately put the unused pages from the address space in swap space
     or waiting until the physical memory to be full to use swap space?
- Q: How do we determine if the page is allocated but not present in memory or
     the page is not allocated at all (segmentation fault)?
  A: We check if the page is allocated or not from the page table entry (PTE),
     and if it has page frame number (PFN), it means that the page is allocated
     (either in memory or disk). That means PFN can hold the memory address or
     disk address (when using swap space), and can be used as indicator whether
     the page is allocated or not.
