- Q: What is the origin of the term daemon in computing?
  A: The term daemon was inspired by the Maxwell's daemon of physics and
     thermodynamics. Maxwell's daemon was an imaginary agent which helped sort
     molecules of different speeds and worked in the background. The term daemon
     used to describe background processes which worked to perform system chores.
- Q: What is the difference between idle memory and inactive memory in `vmstat -a`
     report?
  A: The idle (or free) memory is the memory that's not being used, but the
     inactive memory is the memory that's still allocated but have not been
     used recently. Maybe the example of inactive memory is the stack memory
     that we allocated previously but have not been used recently, so we can
     claim that memory when we need more some memory (?). And it looks like
     "active memory" in `vmstat -a` does not mean the memory in used, it means
     the memory is "recently accessed" and might be needed later on (like
     heap memory which is not in use but have not been freed yet).
     Reference:
     https://linuxvox.com/blog/what-is-active-memory-and-inactive-memory/
- Q: What is the difference between MemFree and MemAvailable in /proc/meminfo?
  A: MemFree is the amount of physical RAM left unused by the system (?).
     MemAvailable is an estimate of how much memory is available for starting
     new applications without swapping. The estimate in MemAvailable takes into
     account that the system needs some page cache to perform well.
     References:
     - https://superuser.com/a/980821
     - https://stackoverflow.com/a/71256266
